<CompareLayout
  title="kerfkit vs OptiCutter (2026) — honest comparison"
  description="OptiCutter is a pro-leaning web optimizer with cost minimization and an API. kerfkit is a native offline app with a one-time price. Honest side-by-side table.">

  <h1>kerfkit vs OptiCutter</h1>
  <p>OptiCutter leans professional: cost-minimization options, multiple unit modes and an API
  for shops that integrate cutting into bigger workflows. kerfkit aims at the workshop itself —
  native, offline, guided cutting at the saw. Here's how they actually differ.</p>

  <div class="tablo-sar">
  <table>
    <tr><th></th><th>kerfkit</th><th>OptiCutter</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Platform</td><td class="iyi">Native iOS (Android on the way)</td><td class="notr">Web only</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Works offline</td><td class="iyi">Fully offline</td><td class="zayif">No</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Free tier</td><td class="iyi">Browser calculator: unlimited calculations</td><td class="zayif">Free tier runs out on real projects</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Price</td><td class="iyi">One-time purchase</td><td class="zayif">€90–190/year (API extra, €99/month)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Cost minimization / pricing</td><td class="zayif">Planned (v1.1 cost + board-foot)</td><td class="iyi">Yes — its strong suit</td></tr>
    <tr><td>API / integrations</td><td class="zayif">Not offered</td><td class="iyi">Yes (paid)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>At-the-saw guidance</td><td class="iyi">Interactive Workshop Mode</td><td class="zayif">Print only</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Grain, kerf, edge banding</td><td class="iyi">Yes</td><td class="iyi">Yes</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Unit handling</td><td class="iyi">mm + fractional inches (1/64″ pad)</td><td class="iyi">5 unit modes</td></tr>
  </table>
  </div>

  <div class="durust"><strong>Where OptiCutter wins today:</strong> material cost optimization
  and API access for production pipelines — if you're quoting jobs or feeding a beam saw from
  software, it's built for that and kerfkit (v1) isn't. If you're a woodworker who wants the
  plan on a phone next to the saw without a yearly bill, that's our side of the street.</div>
</CompareLayout>
